y).  This RMP/PSM program describes the procedures, training, engineering controls and emergency response procedures implemented by CCRWWTF to prevent or minimize the release of hazardous chemicals from its covered processes. 

It is the policy of CCRWWTF that the receipt, storage and handling of chlorine be done in a manner that meets regulatory requirements and minimizes the probability and severity of accidental releases of chlorine into the atmosphere, in order to protect the health and safety of its workers, the public and the environment.  In order to accomplish this goal, CCRWWTF has performed the following tasks:

A?    Gathered safety information on the process, equipment and procedures involving chlorine; 
A?    Performed a structured process hazard analysis (PHA) and evaluated external events that might affect the process; 
A?    Performed an off-site consequences analysis of defined release scenarios; 
A?    Established a written program for prevention and mitigation of accidental releases; and 
A?    Established a written emergency action plan coordinated with emergency response agencies.

An integral part of the RMP/PSM program is the completion of a PHA of the facility's storage and use of chlorine. The PHA was conducted using a WHAT IF? study.  An independent consultant directed a team composed of CCRWWTF personnel with detailed knowledge of the process, through the WHAT IF? study.  The objective of the study was to identify potential hazard scenarios, causes for these hazards, potential consequences associated with these scenarios and appropriate responses or actions to mitigate the identified hazards.  The team used a relative risk ranking based on the probability and severity of the hazards to assign a hazard category to each identified deviation.  The PHA study team evaluated these scenarios and discussed their possible consequences.  For each consequence, the team presented and/or developed a mitigating action to address such occurrences.

